2026-01-12 15:31:00.252279+00	2026-01-12 15:31:00.252289+00	cc0068a5-cb09-440f-9584-fd4ad79d1fcf	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Staying Streamlined: Why a Backup Mask, Cutting Tool, and Spool/DSMB in a Butt Pouch Make Sense</p><p>When it comes to diving, especially in technical environments, staying streamlined is key. Whether you're navigating tight spaces or just trying to reduce drag, every piece of gear needs to have its place. One of the most practical solutions for staying streamlined while keeping essential gear accessible is using a butt pouch. In my case, I picked up an XDeep butt pouch during my cave diving course, and it's been a game-changer. Let me tell you why you should consider adding one to your kit.</p><p>A butt pouch allows you to carry critical backup gear\\\\u2014like a mask, cutting tool, and spool/DSMB\\\\u2014without cluttering the front of your setup. It sits snugly against your backplate, so you don\\\\u2019t feel it during the dive, and it\\\\u2019s easy to access when needed. I\\\\u2019ve added some bungee rings to the backplate to clip onto while diving backmount BPW (Backplate and Wing), and the whole setup stays clean and streamlined.</p><p>One of the benefits of a butt pouch is its simplicity. You don\\\\u2019t have to mess around with bulky side pockets or worry about stuff flapping around during your dive. Everything stays neatly packed away until you need it. This is especially useful for technical diving, where minimal drag and easy access to tools can be the difference between a smooth dive and a frustrating one.</p><p>However, if you\\\\u2019re like me and don\\\\u2019t want to spend a fortune on a brand-name pouch, you can go the DIY route. After buying an expensive one for my course, I ended up picking up some aftermarket pockets for cheap. With a little creativity, I rigged one to function as a butt pouch, and it works just as well as the high-end models. It\\\\u2019s an easy way to save money while keeping your setup streamlined.</p><p>Here's a video where I break down how I set up my butt pouch and show you how to do it yourself. Trust me, once you\\\\u2019ve got one in your kit, you won\\\\u2019t go back. It\\\\u2019s one of those things that makes every dive more efficient, safe, and organized.</p>"}	0	t	01f4b95e-c450-49cc-a419-a0f5c5d76647
2026-01-12 15:31:00.261322+00	2026-01-12 15:31:00.26133+00	74033bce-ab38-4a0b-b016-a4885792f58f	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Food for thought.</p><p>One of the more awkward yet crucial safety skills students stumble with is the low pressure inflator hose disconnect drill.</p><p>The last time I taught for another dive shop the rental gear was so corroded the student couldn't possibly learn the skill.  I myself had a hard time disconnecting the inflator hose.</p><p>This was frustrating for them, and for me.  It's such an important potentially life saving skill. A failed runaway inflater is one of the most common problems that can cause an uncontrolled rapid ascent.</p><p>So something I always do before I teach is to make sure the inflator hose my student has is easy and smooth to operate correctly.</p><p>Regular cleaning with vinegar or a dip in the ultrasonic plus a small dab of silicone applied with the tip of a probe keeps things moving as they should.</p><p>You may wonder why I'm more expensive to study with than the cattle boat operators.  This is one of the reasons.   I make the skills easier to learn because I put more time into the details.  Here's all it takes not to cut corners.  But that costs more because it takes more time in and out of the water and behind the scenes.</p>"}	0	t	6bcfe9ff-a14d-4b83-97a6-5741d60b0bd2
