2026-01-12 15:31:00.313125+00	2026-01-12 15:31:00.313139+00	cc394a53-ff4c-4f98-be17-5acaa8f52df9	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>I just read a post in a diving group from an open water student expressing frustration with their instructor failing to teach them how to succeed in the straightline reciprocal compass navigation requirement.  I was especially disheartened to hear they didn't get the necessary instruction and failed the course and they were not allowed to continue to open water dives 3 & 4.</p><p>First this is a dive optional skill that can be taught and retaught and repeated again and again so it blows my mind any instructor would summarily decide on dive 2 that they would issue the student the intermediate scuba diver certification rather than teach the struggling student and allow them more opportunities to demonstrate it on the next dives in sequence.</p><p>I made a video for this student and others who I hope will benefit from my method of teaching something that takes about three minutes to teach and when paired with some dry land practice guarantees success for meeting the performance requirement.   It really pisses me off when I hear stories like this. It's not only traumatic for the failing student who walks away from the experience with a bad taste in their mouth about dive education it reflects poorly on our profession when instructors dont take the time to teach people who struggle and then fail them.</p><p>This is how I teach the skill.</p>"}	0	t	eb9c410f-1941-46d2-83da-2f1b75af1e50
