2026-01-12 15:31:01.107997+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.108005+00	a791f6e1-2356-4597-aff0-470682c8bec9	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Tiny Arrow Crab at night.   Shot with an Olympus TG-6 and a dive light.</p><p>The Arrow Crab (Stenorhynchus seticornis) is a small, marine crab that is native to the tropical and subtropical waters of the western Atlantic Ocean. These crabs get their name from their distinctive shape, which resembles an arrowhead with long, slender legs.</p><p>Arrow Crabs are typically found in coral reefs, where they can often be seen scurrying among the crevices and hiding among the coral. They are omnivorous and feed on a variety of small invertebrates, including snails, worms, and crustaceans.</p><p>Despite their small size, Arrow Crabs are formidable predators and are known to attack and kill much larger prey, such as fish and octopuses. They are also known to be cannibalistic and will occasionally prey on other Arrow Crabs.</p><p>In addition to their predatory behavior, Arrow Crabs are also known for their intricate courtship rituals. During mating season, male Arrow Crabs will perform elaborate courtship displays for females, waving their claws and legs in an attempt to attract a mate.</p><p>Arrow Crabs are popular among aquarium enthusiasts for their interesting behavior and attractive appearance. They are generally hardy and easy to care for, making them a popular choice for beginner aquarists.</p><p>Despite their popularity in the aquarium trade, Arrow Crabs are not considered to be at risk of extinction in the wild. However, like all marine species, they are vulnerable to habitat destruction and environmental degradation, and it is important to ensure that they are protected and conserved.</p><p>Overall, the tiny Arrow Crab is a fascinating and intriguing creature that is well worth learning about and protecting.</p><p>---</p><p>El cangrejo flecha (Stenorhynchus seticornis) es un peque\\\\u00f1o cangrejo marino nativo de las aguas tropicales y subtropicales del Oc\\\\u00e9ano Atl\\\\u00e1ntico occidental. Estos cangrejos reciben su nombre por su forma distintiva, que se asemeja a una punta de flecha con patas largas y delgadas.</p><p>Los cangrejos flecha se encuentran t\\\\u00edpicamente en los arrecifes de coral, donde a menudo se los puede ver correteando entre las grietas y escondi\\\\u00e9ndose entre los corales. Son omn\\\\u00edvoros y se alimentan de una variedad de peque\\\\u00f1os invertebrados, incluidos caracoles, gusanos y crust\\\\u00e1ceos.</p><p>A pesar de su peque\\\\u00f1o tama\\\\u00f1o, los cangrejos flecha son depredadores formidables y se sabe que atacan y matan presas mucho m\\\\u00e1s grandes, como peces y pulpos. Tambi\\\\u00e9n se sabe que son can\\\\u00edbales y ocasionalmente se alimentan de otros cangrejos flecha.</p><p>Adem\\\\u00e1s de su comportamiento depredador, los cangrejos flecha tambi\\\\u00e9n son conocidos por sus intrincados rituales de cortejo. Durante la temporada de apareamiento, los cangrejos flecha machos realizar\\\\u00e1n elaboradas exhibiciones de cortejo para las hembras, agitando sus garras y patas en un intento de atraer a una pareja.</p><p>Los cangrejos flecha son populares entre los entusiastas de los acuarios por su comportamiento interesante y su apariencia atractiva. Por lo general, son resistentes y f\\\\u00e1ciles de cuidar, lo que los convierte en una opci\\\\u00f3n popular para los acuaristas principiantes.</p><p>A pesar de su popularidad en el comercio de acuarios, no se considera que los cangrejos flecha est\\\\u00e9n en riesgo de extinci\\\\u00f3n en la naturaleza. Sin embargo, como todas las especies marinas, son vulnerables a la destrucci\\\\u00f3n del h\\\\u00e1bitat y la degradaci\\\\u00f3n ambiental, y es importante garantizar su protecci\\\\u00f3n y conservaci\\\\u00f3n.</p><p>En general, el diminuto Cangrejo Flecha es una criatura fascinante e intrigante que vale la pena conocer y proteger.</p>"}	0	t	2663a013-bad8-4343-b1b3-168d5b0524e1
2026-01-12 15:31:01.11627+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.116277+00	1acbb03e-ce68-49cf-95c4-3633364502d9	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>The sun is hot \\nthe ocean is cool\\nIt's a perfect time \\nfor diving school.</p><p>I'm looking for some beta testers for a new remote Learning Management System I'm developing to help students organize their study of the academic parts of PADI course materials and instructor taught (over zoom) remote learning before they get in the water.</p><p>Send me a message if you want to help me with feedback and I'll give you a significant discount on the cost of the PADI courses.</p>"}	0	t	f7260708-696c-4993-ac01-dbda81678daf
2026-01-12 15:31:01.124149+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.124157+00	88192fa9-1cf3-4864-9924-75b4dccffe68	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>I've been following Andy Davis and scubatechphilippines for a while now.  I really appreciate his deep knowledge and longtime experience teaching technical and sidemount diving.</p><p>He shares a ton of information for free and explains things clearly, and with diagrams.  I've learned a lot from reading his articles and as a DIYer myself, I also appreciate him sharing his plans and techniques and encouragement for making ones own gear.</p><p>I've just purchased his new book and already in the first 50 pages I think I've learned twice what I knew so far about sidemount diving.  For 25 bucks this is really a wealth of information any diver interested in sidemount would benefit from.</p><p>In fact his advice to me from a question I asked in a response to one of his posts was worth it right then and there.</p><p>You can find him at Scubatechphilippines on Facebook and at his website of the same name dotcom.  Here is a direct link to his E book.</p>"}	0	t	4645e11c-8065-4383-b9f5-0642fa33b5aa
