2026-01-12 15:31:01.786342+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.786358+00	921e129a-3ba8-4edd-b1f5-b40a0e3e473f	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Today I went to join the Ocean Memory Project and met many community stakeholders that are working to bring awareness and conservation to Puerto Morelos.</p>"}	0	t	d6658aaf-58cb-46b5-9529-b82d4e93c1d4
2026-01-12 15:31:01.798333+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.798343+00	dff6b8d4-599e-45b1-b132-857e40e588b9	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Fear changed to courage!!  \\n#happydiving</p>"}	0	t	51aa8c52-0f70-4a54-82d1-44453ec3c643
2026-01-12 15:31:01.807516+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.807524+00	02860cd6-77db-4a95-8187-ed7ca922bc3c	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>I took a wreck diving instructor course.  One of the skills we learned to teach is laying a line.  Here you can see we are practicing the skill dry.  Mois my instructor is demonstrating how to use a spool and avoid entanglement.</p><p>There are many wrecks in this area, in Florida and in lake Michigan I intend to explore.  Having this certification and set of skills is a great opportunity to share my love of exploring wrecks with other divers.</p><p>Special thanks to the GoPro Family for inviting me to take this course.  The skills I'm learning are invaluable.</p>"}	0	t	79519148-5332-47c6-811a-af8b55d37ec5
2026-01-12 15:31:01.815493+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.8155+00	5e4e3aff-45e8-48d7-825b-067f7df06056	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>The lagoon is full of barracuda.  Here I caught one in the act of snatching up and eating a couple fish before it swam away.</p><p>https://www.facebook.com/575005473/videos/5273120802726142/</p>"}	0	t	f676758b-11ff-409d-87a5-8fedd1fa1304
2026-01-12 15:31:01.82332+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.823328+00	bd0bd8cc-b040-4b1b-971d-01424615ca00	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Kodie came to Mexico to take his open water course with me.  We went on our checkout dives with Ramiro at Scuba Public.  Congrats on your new C card Kodie!</p>"}	0	t	ab8b5ba0-e506-4bf1-b10e-c0c204a772a9
2026-01-12 15:31:01.831187+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.831195+00	0ba9b334-ed74-4278-b16d-67f061c97607	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>How to use dive tables in 34 seconds.  This is about the speed I've heard that some other instructors teach it. In this video however accidentally made it a time lapse.</p><p>I will be happy to slow it down for anyone who wants to learn, and you should.  Knowing how to use tables to plan dives is handy if your computer breaks or if you don't have one, or if you just want to make sure what you are planning to do in your repetitive dives and your actual surface intervals are actually safe.</p>"}	0	t	a7bd6fd5-54ff-41a4-b956-a795e31cd076
2026-01-12 15:31:01.839162+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.83917+00	0882ae6f-437b-4c48-b6f5-d2fcfed81750	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Here are the videos from Kodie's open water dives.  Special thanks to Ramiro at Scuba Public for sharing the videos he made of the experience.</p>"}	0	t	91968fd0-61b1-4f60-a055-5371f6c8e221
2026-01-12 15:31:01.846905+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.846913+00	6d473a0e-50c1-40ab-9301-fe3219b2da5c	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Took Jian on a dive.  I mean, look at this dude.  You'd never guess it was his second time diving ever.  I think he's a good diver in search of more training and many more happy dives. Hopefully some with me again.</p><p>Definitely should take your open water course Jian, and continue your diving experiences.  I'm so stoked that you seem to love diving like I do!</p><p>Special thanks to Jairo and Ana at King Scuba in Puerto Morelos for taking Jian as a client, managing the logistics and equipment for this dive and letting me tag along.  As always Captain Larry made it a smooth ride in the Rubia.\\n#gaydivebuddy #happydiving #padiinstructor #projectaware #kingscuba</p>"}	0	t	4bf771dd-6bd1-4ef7-859c-078432aaeb61
2026-01-12 15:31:01.854905+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.854913+00	b3463af0-a788-44b2-abf7-2443f20fe964	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Today I went shore diving in the lagoon and was able to take my time exploring a small part taking in the details and practicing underwater photography buoyancy and trim skills. I really enjoyed being patient and still in the warm water of the Caribbean, with no rush to swim around.  This gave the sea creatures time to get used to my bubbles.</p><p>At a depth of 5-6 meters my gas consumption was 1000psi every 30 or more minutes.  My dive plan was for 60 minutes.  I notified the park of my plan and went diving.  I did forgot my compass that needs to be replaced it's jacked up.  But I was still able to use the natural navigation details like the current, the angle of the sun (that changes), the ripples in the sand, the surge, and which features of coral and where certain schools of fish tend to live, the temperature, fresh water cenote vents, etc... to find my way back to exactly where on the beach I left my towel and shoes.</p><p>A huevo!</p><p>In July I am going to try to take the Guide course offered by the park.  It's all in Spanish.</p>"}	0	t	71b06281-f5cd-4fa9-96a7-c8c9a76c01ec
2026-01-12 15:31:01.863194+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.863202+00	dc52011d-bbd0-4b91-9cb1-d54408d83df0	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>For those who prefer video action.  Here are a few snippets of what I experience a few times a week.  It's like a morning walk, except in the ocean.  The ocean is 5 minutes from my house here in the Caribbean.  The small town I live in is 20 minutes from the Cancun airport.  I have a spare bedroom for anyone who wants to visit and go diving with me.</p>"}	0	t	34ccfd21-bd68-430e-983e-64b6e9b72718
2026-01-12 15:31:01.871231+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.871241+00	39cef750-4be6-4943-89bc-80d9b8fd8b32	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Jian and his colleague came on a dive with me.  I brought them to King Scuba and they took a basic Discover Scuba Diving class and then we got on a boat and went diving.</p><p>The visibility wasn't that great because of the storms we've been having.  But still they got to experience diving and despite the conditions there were lots of fish and corals to see.</p><p>At the end of the dive we got hungry so we went to eat shrimp tacos at Carabelo's.  Overall it was an awesome day and they'll be back diving with me again!</p>"}	0	t	43bbcff9-0e53-48a1-8ce0-2882968ffc9b
2026-01-12 15:31:01.88745+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.887458+00	dc8fef18-bfd8-42d7-a27b-1b3b9b455d01	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Wind fresh and the water clear.</p><p>What a great day to practice swimming, skin diving, and dive buddy skills.</p><p>Harbor is closed for boats.  But swimming in the waves and current and then hanging out on the resting buoys sure is fun. Being a swimmer is one of the most important skills for diving.  Becoming a strong swimmer takes practice.</p><p>So Kodie and I just finished reviewing these important skills for his open water diver certification.  And he did great in the water! Passed  his swimming tests while having fun.  The swimming test has 2 choices: 1. swim 200 meters without any swimming aids (ie: Laps in the pool) or 2. 300 meters with mask, snorkle and fins.  The float test is float 10 minutes.  It's easy to float in salt water.</p><p>So what better way to enjoy the open water course swimming test than by snorkling an exhilarating ocean drifting down the coast while looking down on some mind-blowing sea creatures on a beautiful day.</p><p>Why swim laps in a pool when you can swim in the ocean, float easily and see cool stuff.!  One on one buddy system is my favorite way to teach my friends who come to visit me.  Thanks Kodie for making the trip!  It's so awesome to see you in real life again!</p>"}	0	t	b6c8b46f-172d-4ad8-8388-f7f140b4da9c
2026-01-12 15:31:01.895485+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.895493+00	5b9d937a-86c5-4657-ad02-51322cae4b96	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Here we are on the shipwreck.  Angie, Ramiro, and I and a couple other divers shared the boat.</p>"}	0	t	72b1bfb4-ecfa-4b40-8068-8ba74f3e1700
2026-01-12 15:31:01.902915+00	2026-01-12 15:31:01.902922+00	10032554-326e-4287-8f04-48784b52769a	\N	rich_text	{"content": "<p>Alberto hovering over the Abyss.</p>"}	0	t	e6c4a659-587d-40d6-a54c-9291cdb56145
