2026-01-09 00:43:47.687236+00	2026-01-09 00:43:47.687273+00	7b33095a-449f-4c72-b465-71542b3f3659	\N	dive-sites/ojo-de-agua	Ojo de Agua Dive Site	published	authenticated	[]	[]					index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/dive-sites/ojo-de-agua/", "slug": "dive-sites/ojo-de-agua", "title": "Ojo de Agua - Dive Site Guide"}, "blocks": [{"id": "hero", "data": {"title": "Ojo de Agua", "subtitle": "Where freshwater springs meet the Caribbean Sea"}, "type": "hero", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "stats", "data": {"stats": [{"label": "Max Depth", "value": "6m / 20ft"}, {"label": "Difficulty", "value": "All Levels"}, {"label": "Certification", "value": "DSD OK"}, {"label": "Visibility", "value": "10-20m"}]}, "type": "stats_row", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "overview-heading", "data": {"text": "Overview", "level": "2"}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "overview", "data": {"content": "\\n                        <p>\\"Ojo de Agua\\" means \\"Eye of Water\\" - named for the freshwater springs that bubble up through the sandy bottom. These cenote-fed springs create a unique environment where cool freshwater mixes with warm seawater, creating mesmerizing visual effects called haloclines.</p>\\n                        <p>The shallow depth and calm conditions make this an ideal site for Discover Scuba Diving experiences, snorkeling, and underwater photography.</p>\\n                        "}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "unique-heading", "data": {"text": "What Makes It Special", "level": "2"}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 4}, {"id": "unique", "data": {"content": "\\n                        <ul>\\n                            <li><strong>Haloclines:</strong> Watch the water \\"shimmer\\" where fresh and salt water mix</li>\\n                            <li><strong>Sandy springs:</strong> See sand dance as freshwater pushes up from below</li>\\n                            <li><strong>Excellent for photos:</strong> Great natural lighting at shallow depth</li>\\n                            <li><strong>Extended bottom time:</strong> No deco concerns at this depth</li>\\n                        </ul>\\n                        "}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 5}, {"id": "marine-heading", "data": {"text": "Marine Life", "level": "2"}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 6}, {"id": "marine", "data": {"content": "\\n                        <ul>\\n                            <li>Juvenile fish using shallow waters as nursery</li>\\n                            <li>Stingrays in the sandy areas</li>\\n                            <li>Sea cucumbers and starfish</li>\\n                            <li>Colorful sponges and soft corals</li>\\n                            <li>Occasional seahorses in the grass</li>\\n                        </ul>\\n                        "}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 7}, {"id": "ideal-for", "data": {"type": "success", "title": "Ideal For", "content": "\\n                        <ul>\\n                            <li>Discover Scuba Diving (DSD) experiences</li>\\n                            <li>Refresher dives after time off</li>\\n                            <li>Underwater photography practice</li>\\n                            <li>Snorkelers wanting to see divers</li>\\n                            <li>Multi-level family trips</li>\\n                        </ul>\\n                        "}, "type": "callout", "sequence": 8}]}	2026-01-09 00:43:47.667591+00	0	t	default	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 00:43:47.701583+00	2026-01-09 00:43:47.701605+00	cdfa3567-11b8-4fc1-b411-c7e72f8ccdb1	\N	dive-sites/the-wall	The Wall Dive Site	published	authenticated	[]	[]					index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/dive-sites/the-wall/", "slug": "dive-sites/the-wall", "title": "The Wall - Dive Site Guide"}, "blocks": [{"id": "hero", "data": {"title": "The Wall", "subtitle": "A dramatic vertical drop into the blue abyss"}, "type": "hero", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "stats", "data": {"stats": [{"label": "Max Depth", "value": "40m / 130ft"}, {"label": "Difficulty", "value": "Advanced"}, {"label": "Certification", "value": "AOW + Deep"}, {"label": "Visibility", "value": "30-50m+"}]}, "type": "stats_row", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "warning", "data": {"type": "warning", "title": "Advanced Dive", "content": "This is a challenging dive requiring excellent buoyancy control and depth awareness. The wall drops beyond recreational limits - respect your training and planned depth."}, "type": "callout", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "overview-heading", "data": {"text": "Overview", "level": "2"}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "overview", "data": {"content": "\\n                        <p>The Wall is our most dramatic dive site - a sheer vertical drop-off that plunges from 15 meters to well beyond recreational diving limits. The reef edge is festooned with massive barrel sponges, black coral trees, and sea fans that sway in the gentle current.</p>\\n                        <p>The wall creates upwellings that bring nutrients from the deep, attracting large pelagic species. Divers often spend the dive at 25-35 meters, drifting along the wall face while scanning the blue for big fish.</p>\\n                        "}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}, {"id": "marine-heading", "data": {"text": "Marine Life", "level": "2"}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 5}, {"id": "marine", "data": {"content": "\\n                        <p><strong>Pelagic encounters:</strong></p>\\n                        <ul>\\n                            <li>Caribbean reef sharks patrolling the wall</li>\\n                            <li>Eagle rays gliding past</li>\\n                            <li>Large schools of jacks and horse-eye</li>\\n                            <li>Occasional bull sharks (winter months)</li>\\n                            <li>Manta rays (rare but possible)</li>\\n                        </ul>\\n                        <p><strong>On the wall:</strong></p>\\n                        <ul>\\n                            <li>Giant barrel sponges (some 6+ feet tall)</li>\\n                            <li>Black coral trees</li>\\n                            <li>Deep-water gorgonians</li>\\n                            <li>Flamingo tongue snails on sea fans</li>\\n                        </ul>\\n                        "}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 6}, {"id": "requirements", "data": {"type": "error", "title": "Mandatory Requirements", "content": "\\n                        <ul>\\n                            <li>Advanced Open Water + Deep Diver specialty</li>\\n                            <li>Minimum 50 logged dives</li>\\n                            <li>Dive computer mandatory (no tables)</li>\\n                            <li>SMB required for all divers</li>\\n                            <li>Recent diving experience (within 6 months)</li>\\n                        </ul>\\n                        "}, "type": "callout", "sequence": 7}, {"id": "tips-heading", "data": {"text": "Dive Planning", "level": "2"}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 8}, {"id": "tips", "data": {"content": "\\n                        <ul>\\n                            <li><strong>Typical profile:</strong> Descend to 35-40m, slowly ascend along wall, safety stop at 5m</li>\\n                            <li><strong>Bottom time:</strong> 20-25 minutes at depth before ascending</li>\\n                            <li><strong>Gas planning:</strong> Plan for 50 bar reserve minimum</li>\\n                            <li><strong>Current:</strong> Can be moderate - drift diving common</li>\\n                            <li><strong>Best conditions:</strong> Calm seas, morning dives for best visibility</li>\\n                        </ul>\\n                        "}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 9}]}	2026-01-09 00:43:47.698812+00	0	t	default	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.707931+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.104866+00	a83d34fc-7785-4ec6-ac37-3a8cd7aff249	\N	help-getting-started-navigation-guide	Navigation Guide	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>The staff portal uses a consistent navigation structure across all pages.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Sidebar Navigation</h3>\\n<p>The left sidebar is organized into logical sections:</p>\\n\\n<h4>Dive Operations</h4>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Excursions</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/excursions/</code>) - Schedule and manage dive trips</li>\\n    <li><strong>Divers</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/divers/</code>) - Diver profiles and certifications</li>\\n    <li><strong>Dive Sites</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/sites/</code>) - Location details and photos</li>\\n    <li><strong>Protected Areas</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/protected-areas/</code>) - Marine parks, permits, fees</li>\\n    <li><strong>Agreements</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/signable-agreements/</code>) - Waivers and contracts</li>\\n    <li><strong>Medical Questionnaires</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/medical/</code>) - Health screening</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h4>Planning</h4>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Dive Plans</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/dive-plans/</code>) - Pre-dive briefings and profiles</li>\\n    <li><strong>Dive Logs</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/dive-logs/</code>) - Post-dive records</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h4>Configuration</h4>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Excursion Types</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/excursion-types/</code>) - Trip templates with pricing</li>\\n    <li><strong>Agreement Types</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/agreements/templates/</code>) - Document templates</li>\\n    <li><strong>Catalog Items</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/catalog/</code>) - Products and services</li>\\n    <li><strong>AI Settings</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/settings/ai/</code>) - AI feature configuration</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h4>Finance</h4>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Chart of Accounts</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/accounts/</code>) - Ledger accounts</li>\\n    <li><strong>Payables</strong> (<code>/staff/diveops/payables/</code>) - Vendor invoices and payments</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.104753+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.717212+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.114215+00	c48df9be-c104-432a-be07-f8ceeb7c2888	\N	help-getting-started-your-account	Your Account	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Staff accounts provide access to the dive operations dashboard based on assigned roles.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Account Access</h3>\\n<p>Your account provides access based on your staff permissions. The system tracks all actions in the audit log for accountability.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Profile Link</h3>\\n<p>Click <strong>Profile</strong> in the sidebar to access your personal settings. Click <strong>Log out</strong> to end your session.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Session Security</h3>\\n<p>Sessions expire after a period of inactivity. For security, always log out when using shared computers.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.114113+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-11 11:05:38.961162+00	2026-01-11 11:05:38.974484+00	5375ce84-24dc-4a33-a2a9-0de89157fb0a	2026-01-12 13:38:33.912871+00	choosing-first-wetsuit	How to Choose Your First Wetsuit: A Complete Guide	published	public	[]	[]	How to Choose Your First Wetsuit: A Complete Guide	Everything you need to know about selecting the right wetsuit for your diving needs, from thickness and material to fit and features.			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/choosing-first-wetsuit/", "slug": "choosing-first-wetsuit", "title": "How to Choose Your First Wetsuit: A Complete Guide", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "How to Choose Your First Wetsuit: A Complete Guide", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "Everything you need to know about selecting the right wetsuit for your diving needs, from thickness and material to fit and features."}, "blocks": [{"id": "58f27b8c-247d-4b2a-9530-8fbd6c33b17b", "data": {"content": "<p>A wetsuit is one of the most important pieces of diving equipment you'll own. It keeps you warm, protects you from stings and scrapes, and can even add buoyancy. But with so many options available, how do you choose the right one?</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "55836240-9dcd-4949-a29f-669af8280499", "data": {"text": "Understanding Wetsuit Thickness", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "781b4972-702d-4e72-bc44-a675ba6c6a4b", "data": {"content": "<ul><li><strong>3mm</strong> - Warm tropical waters (80F/27C and above)</li><li><strong>5mm</strong> - Temperate waters (68-80F/20-27C)</li><li><strong>7mm</strong> - Cold water diving (50-68F/10-20C)</li><li><strong>Semi-dry or Drysuit</strong> - Very cold water (below 50F/10C)</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "45867be5-f8f3-43dd-a6ae-1471421d0cd9", "data": {"text": "Getting the Right Fit", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "862d8a84-a66b-4384-aced-90e6e23a7447", "data": {"content": "<p>A properly fitting wetsuit should be snug but not restrictive. Water should not flow freely through the suit, but you should still be able to move and breathe comfortably. Here are key fit points to check:</p><ul><li>No gaps at the neck, wrists, or ankles</li><li>Smooth contact across the back with no air pockets</li><li>Full range of motion in arms and legs</li><li>Comfortable when bending at waist and knees</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}], "version": 1, "checksum": "2d0c74a8fd79192822e0c101f31d45e09ef9a90d5d37c3bd98f0841f959cbfc1", "published_at": "2026-01-11T11:05:38.974375+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-11 11:05:38.974375+00	0	t	default	{}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	Everything you need to know about selecting the right wetsuit for your diving needs, from thickness and material to fit and features.	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1682687220742-aba13b6e50ba?w=1200	post	6	["wetsuit", "gear", "beginners", "equipment", "thermal protection"]	528539c7-df36-4c51-adb7-eab4464ceedb
2026-01-11 11:05:38.97657+00	2026-01-11 11:05:39.001586+00	a1ab91bc-f123-44ec-9004-e74c6c92d9cc	2026-01-12 13:38:33.943536+00	open-water-certification-guide	Your Complete Guide to Open Water Certification	published	public	[]	[]	Your Complete Guide to Open Water Certification	Everything you need to know about getting your Open Water diving certification, from choosing an agency to what to expect during the course.			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/open-water-certification-guide/", "slug": "open-water-certification-guide", "title": "Your Complete Guide to Open Water Certification", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "Your Complete Guide to Open Water Certification", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "Everything you need to know about getting your Open Water diving certification, from choosing an agency to what to expect during the course."}, "blocks": [{"id": "4f36063c-a3ae-4695-9a03-68d201693cac", "data": {"content": "<p>Getting your Open Water certification is your ticket to exploring the underwater world. This certification allows you to dive independently with a buddy to depths of 18 meters (60 feet) anywhere in the world. Here's everything you need to know about the process.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "77a0e756-fb68-4c7f-9e60-91ad5ec0b620", "data": {"text": "Choosing a Certification Agency", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "a2c480c1-5224-4aac-aff6-38388b28c402", "data": {"content": "<p>The two most popular certification agencies are <strong>PADI</strong> (Professional Association of Diving Instructors) and <strong>SSI</strong> (Scuba Schools International). Both are recognized worldwide and offer comparable training. The choice often comes down to which agency your local dive shop is affiliated with.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "454cf9cf-316f-4147-882e-32cb6a1c5f7d", "data": {"text": "Course Structure", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "c6fa5523-bbc5-495b-9e95-316bd7f6e7a6", "data": {"content": "<p>The Open Water course typically includes:</p><ul><li><strong>Knowledge Development</strong> - Online or classroom learning covering dive theory</li><li><strong>Confined Water Dives</strong> - Pool sessions to practice skills in controlled environment</li><li><strong>Open Water Dives</strong> - 4 dives in open water demonstrating mastery of skills</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}, {"id": "7ae53a03-5222-491f-8451-2cf48c2f99bb", "data": {"text": "Prerequisites", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 5}, {"id": "8e570f25-40c0-4363-be86-4f0742e1ecfa", "data": {"content": "<p>To enroll in an Open Water course, you must:</p><ul><li>Be at least 10 years old (Junior Open Water) or 15 years old (Open Water)</li><li>Be comfortable in the water and able to swim</li><li>Complete a medical questionnaire (some conditions require physician clearance)</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 6}], "version": 1, "checksum": "d6ddc19740481b2ee6b1a001db8c6429c07f20da07348d1d391aa1693be479c4", "published_at": "2026-01-11T11:05:39.001149+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-11 11:05:39.001149+00	0	t	default	{}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	Everything you need to know about getting your Open Water diving certification, from choosing an agency to what to expect during the course.	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559827260-dc66d52bef19?w=1200	post	10	["certification", "padi", "ssi", "open water", "beginners", "training"]	ed7c20ef-67c7-43fa-8a67-411beacc8d5d
2026-01-11 11:05:39.00472+00	2026-01-11 11:05:39.017718+00	9fcbf843-5417-4a36-86ff-1f427d06335b	2026-01-12 13:38:33.978142+00	sea-turtle-encounters	Sea Turtle Encounters: A Diver's Guide to These Gentle Giants	published	public	[]	[]	Sea Turtle Encounters: A Diver's Guide to These Gentle Giants	Learn about the different species of sea turtles you might encounter while diving, their behaviors, and how to observe them responsibly.			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/sea-turtle-encounters/", "slug": "sea-turtle-encounters", "title": "Sea Turtle Encounters: A Diver's Guide to These Gentle Giants", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "Sea Turtle Encounters: A Diver's Guide to These Gentle Giants", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "Learn about the different species of sea turtles you might encounter while diving, their behaviors, and how to observe them responsibly."}, "blocks": [{"id": "0eaf29c8-72d2-40a8-98bd-4be1464b7f67", "data": {"content": "<p>Few underwater encounters are as magical as coming face-to-face with a sea turtle. These ancient mariners have been swimming our oceans for over 100 million years, and as divers, we have the privilege of sharing their underwater world.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "a21552c9-df06-4dbc-a31d-84dd5ac8d497", "data": {"text": "Species You Might Encounter", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "37f0bc4e-379e-47b7-b10d-4dac39c9b7db", "data": {"content": "<p><strong>Green Sea Turtle</strong> - The most commonly encountered species, named for the green color of their fat. Often seen grazing on seagrass beds.</p><p><strong>Hawksbill Turtle</strong> - Recognizable by their pointed beak and beautiful patterned shell. Frequently found on coral reefs feeding on sponges.</p><p><strong>Loggerhead Turtle</strong> - Named for their large heads, these powerful swimmers are often seen in temperate waters.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "62d96b4d-cf24-4428-b00e-e705f3cecdf1", "data": {"text": "Responsible Turtle Watching", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "f4f1262a-1d71-4605-bd21-ddc5ef3fcf9a", "data": {"content": "<ul><li>Keep a respectful distance of at least 2 meters (6 feet)</li><li>Never touch, chase, or ride sea turtles</li><li>Avoid blocking their path to the surface - they need to breathe!</li><li>Don't use flash photography</li><li>Let them approach you rather than swimming after them</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}], "version": 1, "checksum": "e158b9c7b2087a8d77a1068855fd36f2f44891fd8d7d99c22cfcf10fb4133b1c", "published_at": "2026-01-11T11:05:39.017582+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-11 11:05:39.017582+00	0	t	default	{}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	Learn about the different species of sea turtles you might encounter while diving, their behaviors, and how to observe them responsibly.	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1591025207163-942350e47db2?w=1200	post	7	["sea turtles", "marine life", "wildlife", "conservation", "underwater photography"]	20cbe38f-ca35-431a-88d1-3980aef359fb
2026-01-11 11:05:39.020569+00	2026-01-11 11:05:39.037607+00	c1c79b4f-ba39-476e-ab2a-b3d64f6691f2	2026-01-12 13:38:34.006967+00	understanding-dcs	Understanding Decompression Sickness: Prevention and Recognition	published	public	[]	[]	Understanding Decompression Sickness: Prevention and Recognition	A comprehensive guide to decompression sickness (the bends), including risk factors, symptoms, prevention strategies, and what to do if you suspect DCS.			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/understanding-dcs/", "slug": "understanding-dcs", "title": "Understanding Decompression Sickness: Prevention and Recognition", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "Understanding Decompression Sickness: Prevention and Recognition", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "A comprehensive guide to decompression sickness (the bends), including risk factors, symptoms, prevention strategies, and what to do if you suspect DCS."}, "blocks": [{"id": "102b1085-5713-448e-b74e-884d8f135eb4", "data": {"content": "<p>Decompression sickness (DCS), commonly known as \\"the bends,\\" is one of the most serious risks divers face. Understanding what causes it, how to prevent it, and how to recognize symptoms is essential knowledge for every diver.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "cd40dd76-dfef-4fa3-abd2-c7c56716bfb4", "data": {"text": "What Causes DCS?", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "46832208-2516-40a7-a5f3-8015b0789e7b", "data": {"content": "<p>During a dive, nitrogen from the air we breathe dissolves into our body tissues under pressure. If we ascend too quickly, this nitrogen can form bubbles in our tissues and bloodstream, similar to how bubbles form when opening a carbonated drink. These bubbles can cause a range of symptoms from mild joint pain to life-threatening neurological damage.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "82fc295b-d830-4223-bfc4-227d69a4e2cd", "data": {"text": "Prevention Strategies", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "3fd5ef62-bfcf-497f-a9a6-19c534ea61c5", "data": {"content": "<ul><li>Always follow your dive computer or tables</li><li>Ascend slowly - no faster than 30 feet (9m) per minute</li><li>Perform safety stops at 15 feet (5m) for 3-5 minutes</li><li>Stay well hydrated before and after diving</li><li>Avoid flying within 18-24 hours after diving</li><li>Don't push no-decompression limits</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}, {"id": "9015673b-cf0b-4f6e-8528-2991b2174bb3", "data": {"text": "Recognizing Symptoms", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 5}, {"id": "e86ea064-43fb-4c76-b39c-192cc270e65c", "data": {"content": "<p>Symptoms can appear immediately or up to 24 hours after diving:</p><ul><li>Joint pain (especially shoulders, elbows, knees)</li><li>Fatigue or unusual tiredness</li><li>Skin rash or itching</li><li>Dizziness or vertigo</li><li>Numbness or tingling</li><li>Difficulty breathing</li></ul><p><strong>If you suspect DCS, seek emergency medical care immediately and contact DAN (Divers Alert Network).</strong></p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 6}], "version": 1, "checksum": "3b5587ace65e61c5422ec33065fc368bc4b8c2c274a0fa0a71b1a9a61969cc85", "published_at": "2026-01-11T11:05:39.037460+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-11 11:05:39.03746+00	0	t	default	{}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	A comprehensive guide to decompression sickness (the bends), including risk factors, symptoms, prevention strategies, and what to do if you suspect DCS.	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1544551763-77ef2d0cfc6c?w=1200	post	9	["safety", "dcs", "decompression", "health", "emergency"]	2bca00ce-93d7-427d-bf4a-b0ecf45207c8
2026-01-11 11:05:39.040554+00	2026-01-11 11:05:39.054062+00	3f32d60a-de06-42ea-a122-9bc44ac2531b	2026-01-12 13:38:34.04667+00	coral-reef-conservation	Coral Reef Conservation: How Divers Can Make a Difference	published	public	[]	[]	Coral Reef Conservation: How Divers Can Make a Difference	Discover the threats facing coral reefs worldwide and learn practical ways you can help protect these vital ecosystems as a diver.			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/coral-reef-conservation/", "slug": "coral-reef-conservation", "title": "Coral Reef Conservation: How Divers Can Make a Difference", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "Coral Reef Conservation: How Divers Can Make a Difference", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "Discover the threats facing coral reefs worldwide and learn practical ways you can help protect these vital ecosystems as a diver."}, "blocks": [{"id": "f7ab03a6-4a01-49c1-8a35-933187e9ccd4", "data": {"content": "<p>Coral reefs cover less than 1% of the ocean floor but support approximately 25% of all marine species. As divers, we have a unique connection to these underwater ecosystems and a responsibility to help protect them for future generations.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "3bc955ff-6aac-4ee5-893c-a53e701d79ce", "data": {"text": "Threats to Coral Reefs", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "ab67b707-02a8-476f-9953-dd1f43828d5f", "data": {"content": "<p>Coral reefs face numerous threats, both local and global:</p><ul><li><strong>Climate Change</strong> - Rising ocean temperatures cause coral bleaching</li><li><strong>Ocean Acidification</strong> - Absorbed CO2 makes it harder for corals to build skeletons</li><li><strong>Pollution</strong> - Runoff from agriculture and urban areas</li><li><strong>Overfishing</strong> - Disrupts reef ecosystem balance</li><li><strong>Physical Damage</strong> - Anchor damage, careless divers, and destructive fishing practices</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "f7e6137a-335b-4e0f-a411-544833fddd07", "data": {"text": "How Divers Can Help", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "f79a2c01-3a24-417a-866f-85355665c083", "data": {"content": "<ul><li><strong>Perfect Your Buoyancy</strong> - Good buoyancy control prevents accidental reef contact</li><li><strong>Choose Reef-Safe Sunscreen</strong> - Avoid oxybenzone and octinoxate</li><li><strong>Participate in Reef Cleanups</strong> - Remove debris and fishing line</li><li><strong>Report Marine Life Sightings</strong> - Citizen science helps researchers track reef health</li><li><strong>Support Conservation Organizations</strong> - Donate to or volunteer with reef protection groups</li><li><strong>Spread Awareness</strong> - Share your underwater experiences and educate others</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}], "version": 1, "checksum": "c99aa7c23d72ce7b6026d8bd9d25d96a95e229ccc5f856dcab9d6938dca456a7", "published_at": "2026-01-11T11:05:39.053928+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-11 11:05:39.053928+00	0	t	default	{}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	Discover the threats facing coral reefs worldwide and learn practical ways you can help protect these vital ecosystems as a diver.	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1546026423-cc4642628d2b?w=1200	post	8	["conservation", "coral reef", "environment", "sustainability", "ocean health"]	f388f766-ec9e-422e-8903-4d81d981bfb7
2026-01-11 11:05:39.057312+00	2026-01-11 11:05:39.074464+00	b09608ff-9758-4101-bc67-f8281ae75694	2026-01-12 13:38:34.076776+00	night-dive-encounter-with-octopus	My Unforgettable Night Dive Encounter with a Giant Pacific Octopus	published	public	[]	[]	My Unforgettable Night Dive Encounter with a Giant Pacific Octopus	A personal account of an extraordinary night dive in the Pacific Northwest and an unexpected encounter with one of the ocean's most intelligent creatures.			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/night-dive-encounter-with-octopus/", "slug": "night-dive-encounter-with-octopus", "title": "My Unforgettable Night Dive Encounter with a Giant Pacific Octopus", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "My Unforgettable Night Dive Encounter with a Giant Pacific Octopus", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "A personal account of an extraordinary night dive in the Pacific Northwest and an unexpected encounter with one of the ocean's most intelligent creatures."}, "blocks": [{"id": "58a80315-497b-41ee-94b7-752c5dd9094c", "data": {"content": "<p>It was a cold February evening when I slipped beneath the dark waters of Puget Sound. Night diving in the Pacific Northwest isn't for everyone - the water temperature hovered around 45F (7C), and visibility after sunset can be unpredictable. But something kept drawing me back to these waters, and on this particular night, I would discover why.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "c4857cb5-ce13-4ad8-bacc-2c6a6fb1f99f", "data": {"text": "The Descent", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "8454c43d-102a-4324-8ffc-b06d98556efd", "data": {"content": "<p>My dive buddy and I descended along the rocky wall, our primary lights cutting narrow paths through the darkness. The beam revealed sleeping rockfish tucked into crevices and tiny shrimp whose eyes reflected our lights like scattered stars. At about 40 feet, something unusual caught my attention - a subtle movement in the rocks that didn't match the gentle surge.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "d80bf26c-2808-4e5d-bf62-323a4e7ef634", "data": {"text": "The Encounter", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "ef42d678-61bb-4bf1-acbf-a761c177e638", "data": {"content": "<p>I swept my light across the area and there she was - a Giant Pacific Octopus, easily five feet from arm tip to arm tip, watching me with those remarkable, intelligent eyes. Instead of retreating into her den, she seemed curious, extending one arm toward my light while the others remained anchored to the rocks.</p><p>For nearly twenty minutes, we observed each other. She changed colors constantly - from deep red to mottled brown to almost white - and at one point reached out to touch my gloved hand with a single exploring arm. The suckers gripped briefly before releasing, as if testing whether I was friend or food (or perhaps just confused).</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}, {"id": "29dd5deb-7a8b-4f81-bf68-35ac596a6156", "data": {"text": "A Lasting Impression", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 5}, {"id": "6ccad780-67ca-435b-a515-a0d56fe3c8f2", "data": {"content": "<p>That encounter changed how I think about diving and marine life. These creatures aren't just animals to photograph or check off a list - they're individuals with their own curiosity and intelligence. Every dive now feels like an opportunity for connection, a chance to be a guest in someone else's world.</p><p>If you ever get the chance to night dive in the Pacific Northwest, take it. You never know who you might meet in the darkness.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 6}], "version": 1, "checksum": "08c95442a79369395a9d997e2c573dc26b9b92712e83c7cfe4d33e49e35b2c86", "published_at": "2026-01-11T11:05:39.074310+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-11 11:05:39.07431+00	0	t	default	{}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	A personal account of an extraordinary night dive in the Pacific Northwest and an unexpected encounter with one of the ocean's most intelligent creatures.	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1545671913-b89ac1b4ac10?w=1200	post	5	["night diving", "octopus", "pacific northwest", "personal story", "adventure"]	315ad31d-a336-468b-abcf-ae2838203025
2026-01-09 15:42:29.762671+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.157217+00	817f3f1b-2bdc-4b0a-90ed-6a309a444ce1	\N	help-bookings-scheduling-excursions	Scheduling Excursions	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Excursions are single-day operational units representing scheduled dive trips.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Creating an Excursion</h3>\\n<ol>\\n    <li>Navigate to <strong>Excursions</strong></li>\\n    <li>Click <strong>New Excursion</strong></li>\\n    <li>Select an <strong>Excursion Type</strong> (template with defaults)</li>\\n    <li>Set <strong>Date</strong> and <strong>Departure Time</strong></li>\\n    <li>Choose <strong>Dive Site</strong> (optional - can have multiple via dives)</li>\\n    <li>Set <strong>Maximum Divers</strong> capacity</li>\\n    <li>Set <strong>Price per Diver</strong> (pre-filled from type)</li>\\n    <li>Click <strong>Create</strong></li>\\n</ol>\\n\\n<h3>Excursion Types</h3>\\n<p>ExcursionType models serve as templates defining:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Name and description</strong></li>\\n    <li><strong>Dive mode</strong> - boat, shore, cenote, cavern</li>\\n    <li><strong>Time of day</strong> - morning, afternoon, night</li>\\n    <li><strong>Duration</strong> - typical_duration_minutes</li>\\n    <li><strong>Dives per excursion</strong> - number of dives included</li>\\n    <li><strong>Base price</strong> - default pricing</li>\\n    <li><strong>Certification requirements</strong> - minimum level required</li>\\n    <li><strong>Suitable sites</strong> - M2M relationship (empty = all sites)</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Excursion Status Workflow</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>scheduled</strong> - Future trip, accepting bookings</li>\\n    <li><strong>boarding</strong> - Check-in in progress</li>\\n    <li><strong>in_progress</strong> - Trip underway</li>\\n    <li><strong>completed</strong> - Trip finished</li>\\n    <li><strong>cancelled</strong> - Trip cancelled</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Capacity Management</h3>\\n<p>The <code>spots_available</code> property calculates remaining capacity. The <code>is_full</code> property indicates when max_divers is reached.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.157121+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.776655+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.174207+00	d44f802e-94eb-49aa-aaaf-afb733c31f32	\N	help-bookings-check-in-process	Check-in Process	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Check-in is managed through the ExcursionRoster model which tracks actual participants.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Check-in Workflow</h3>\\n<ol>\\n    <li>Open the excursion on departure day</li>\\n    <li>View the booking list</li>\\n    <li>For each arriving diver, click to mark check-in</li>\\n    <li>System records <code>checked_in_at</code> timestamp and <code>checked_in_by</code> staff</li>\\n</ol>\\n\\n<h3>Roster Roles</h3>\\n<p>Each roster entry can have a role:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Diver</strong> - Customer participant</li>\\n    <li><strong>Divemaster</strong> - Professional leading the dive</li>\\n    <li><strong>Instructor</strong> - Teaching role</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Dive Completion</h3>\\n<p>After the excursion, mark <code>dive_completed</code> status for each participant. Notes can be added to individual roster entries.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Excursion Status Transitions</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Use <strong>Start Excursion</strong> to change status to <code>in_progress</code></li>\\n    <li>Use <strong>Complete Excursion</strong> to change status to <code>completed</code></li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.174104+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.789391+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.195028+00	6c3cb5be-f01e-4c18-8fcc-a76b69331c0d	\N	help-bookings-cancellations-refunds	Cancellations & Refunds	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Booking cancellations and financial settlements are handled through the SettlementRecord model.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Cancelling a Booking</h3>\\n<ol>\\n    <li>Open the booking</li>\\n    <li>Click <strong>Cancel Booking</strong></li>\\n    <li>Booking status changes to <code>cancelled</code></li>\\n    <li><code>cancelled_at</code> timestamp is recorded</li>\\n</ol>\\n\\n<h3>Settlement Types</h3>\\n<p>SettlementRecord tracks financial transactions:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>revenue</strong> - Payment received</li>\\n    <li><strong>refund</strong> - Payment returned</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Idempotent Settlements</h3>\\n<p>Each settlement has a unique <code>idempotency_key</code> preventing duplicate processing. The system generates deterministic keys based on booking and transaction type.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Financial State</h3>\\n<p>Bookings track financial state through:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><code>is_settled</code> - Whether payment is complete</li>\\n    <li><code>has_refund</code> - Whether refund was issued</li>\\n    <li><code>get_financial_state()</code> - Current state summary</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Protection Against Deletion</h3>\\n<p>Settled bookings cannot be deleted to preserve financial records. Use soft delete (<code>deleted_at</code>) instead.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.194911+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.803553+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.215641+00	77db8ce6-c8ce-46e1-90d9-a01a5679eec7	\N	help-agreements-sending-for-signature	Sending for Signature	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Agreements use secure token-based access for the signing process.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Access Token Security</h3>\\n<p>Each agreement generates:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Cryptographically random access token</li>\\n    <li>SHA-256 hash stored (raw token never stored)</li>\\n    <li><code>token_consumed</code> flag for one-time use</li>\\n    <li><code>expires_at</code> enforcement at signing time</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Delivery Methods</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Email</strong> - System sends email with secure signing link</li>\\n    <li><strong>Link</strong> - Copy URL to share via text, WhatsApp, etc.</li>\\n    <li><strong>In Person</strong> - Diver signs on shop device</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Resending</h3>\\n<p>For agreements in <code>sent</code> status, use <strong>Resend</strong> to generate a new token and send again. Previous tokens are invalidated.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Expiration Options</h3>\\n<p>Signing links can expire in:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>7 days (default)</li>\\n    <li>14 days</li>\\n    <li>30 days</li>\\n    <li>60 days</li>\\n    <li>90 days</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.215476+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.818592+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.239825+00	fbbf996e-7f3a-41c0-86e0-02aad3c9f38c	\N	help-agreements-voiding-agreements	Voiding Agreements	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Voiding cancels an agreement before it is signed.</p>\\n\\n<h3>When to Void</h3>\\n<p>Void an agreement when:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Created in error</li>\\n    <li>Wrong template selected</li>\\n    <li>Wrong diver associated</li>\\n    <li>Related booking cancelled</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Voiding Restrictions</h3>\\n<p><strong>Important:</strong> Only agreements in <code>draft</code> or <code>sent</code> status can be voided.</p>\\n<p>Signed agreements are legal documents and cannot be voided. To nullify a signed agreement, create a <strong>Revocation Agreement</strong> that the diver must also sign.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Voiding Process</h3>\\n<ol>\\n    <li>Open the agreement (must be draft or sent)</li>\\n    <li>Click <strong>Void Agreement</strong></li>\\n    <li>Enter required reason for voiding</li>\\n    <li>Confirm the action</li>\\n</ol>\\n\\n<h3>Revision History</h3>\\n<p>SignableAgreementRevision maintains an immutable audit trail of all content changes, including voiding. Each revision records:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><code>revision_number</code></li>\\n    <li><code>previous</code> and <code>new content_hash</code></li>\\n    <li><code>change_note</code> (required explanation)</li>\\n    <li><code>changed_by</code> staff member</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.239706+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.825587+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.25141+00	a321255e-4722-483e-8c23-12d3d9ab79c2	\N	help-medical-medical-questionnaires	Medical Questionnaires	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Medical questionnaires screen divers for health conditions that may affect diving safety, based on RSTC/DAN Medical Statement guidelines.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Questionnaire List</h3>\\n<p>The medical questionnaires page (<code>/staff/diveops/medical/</code>) displays:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>All submitted questionnaires</li>\\n    <li>Status filters for reviewing</li>\\n    <li>Diver information and submission date</li>\\n    <li>Flagged conditions count</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Sending Questionnaires</h3>\\n<p>Questionnaires can be sent:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>From diver profile medical tab</li>\\n    <li>Automatically when creating first booking</li>\\n    <li>On annual renewal dates</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Integration with django-questionnaires</h3>\\n<p>The medical system uses the django-questionnaires package for form rendering and response collection.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.251292+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.832584+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.262551+00	142dfdb1-3713-45fa-8b40-dca9cf93c178	\N	help-medical-reviewing-responses	Reviewing Responses	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Staff review completed questionnaires to determine diving eligibility.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Review Workflow</h3>\\n<ol>\\n    <li>Navigate to <strong>Medical Questionnaires</strong></li>\\n    <li>Filter for pending review status</li>\\n    <li>Open questionnaire to see all responses</li>\\n    <li>Review flagged conditions</li>\\n    <li>Make clearance decision</li>\\n</ol>\\n\\n<h3>Flagged Conditions</h3>\\n<p>Certain \\"Yes\\" answers automatically flag for review:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Cardiovascular conditions</li>\\n    <li>Respiratory conditions</li>\\n    <li>Neurological conditions (seizures, blackouts)</li>\\n    <li>Diabetes requiring medication</li>\\n    <li>Recent surgery or illness</li>\\n    <li>Current medications</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Medical Status Determination</h3>\\n<p>The <code>get_diver_medical_status()</code> service returns:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>cleared</strong> - Approved for diving</li>\\n    <li><strong>restricted</strong> - Approved with limitations</li>\\n    <li><strong>needs_review</strong> - Requires staff evaluation</li>\\n    <li><strong>denied</strong> - Not approved for diving</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.262394+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.846689+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.284944+00	5ee2edec-505d-44a9-8955-0a525ba45f99	\N	help-medical-retention-policies	Retention Policies	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Medical records are subject to retention policies and privacy requirements.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Document Retention</h3>\\n<p>The DocumentRetentionPolicy model manages automatic document lifecycle:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Retention period definition</li>\\n    <li>Automatic purge scheduling</li>\\n    <li>Legal hold capability (DocumentLegalHold)</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Privacy Considerations</h3>\\n<p>Medical information is protected:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Access limited to authorized staff</li>\\n    <li>Audit logging of all access</li>\\n    <li>Secure storage and transmission</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Retention Administration</h3>\\n<p>Staff can manage retention policies through:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>RetentionPolicyListView</li>\\n    <li>RetentionPolicyCreateView</li>\\n    <li>RetentionPolicyUpdateView</li>\\n    <li>RetentionPolicyDeleteView</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.284824+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.856591+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.304986+00	d87e9555-6676-4856-9f3d-1e4ea2e3f207	\N	help-protected-areas-fee-schedules	Fee Schedules	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>ProtectedAreaFeeSchedule configures fees for diving activities in protected areas.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Fee Types</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>per_person</strong> - Charged per diver</li>\\n    <li><strong>per_boat</strong> - Charged per vessel</li>\\n    <li><strong>per_trip</strong> - Charged per excursion</li>\\n    <li><strong>per_day</strong> - Daily fee</li>\\n    <li><strong>per_activity</strong> - Activity-specific fee</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Activity Scope</h3>\\n<p>Fees can apply to:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>diving</li>\\n    <li>snorkeling</li>\\n    <li>kayaking</li>\\n    <li>fishing</li>\\n    <li>all activities</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Fee Tiers</h3>\\n<p>ProtectedAreaFeeTier allows tiered pricing:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>tourist</strong> - Standard tourist rate</li>\\n    <li><strong>national</strong> - National citizen rate</li>\\n    <li><strong>local</strong> - Local resident rate</li>\\n    <li><strong>student</strong> - Student discount</li>\\n    <li><strong>senior</strong> - Senior discount</li>\\n    <li><strong>child</strong> - Child rate (age_min, age_max)</li>\\n    <li><strong>infant</strong> - Infant (usually free)</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Eligibility Proof</h3>\\n<p>DiverEligibilityProof tracks documentation for tier qualification:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Proof types: student_id, national_id, resident_card, passport, birth_cert</li>\\n    <li>Status: pending, verified, rejected</li>\\n    <li>Expiration tracking for time-limited proofs</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.304863+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.864917+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.323669+00	05c8f67a-89f2-402b-a979-4162e3c3a242	\N	help-system-document-management	Document Management	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>The document browser (<code>/staff/diveops/documents/</code>) provides file storage and organization.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Document Browser Features</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Folder-based organization</li>\\n    <li>File upload and download</li>\\n    <li>Preview for common file types</li>\\n    <li>Search functionality</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Document Types Used</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Certification cards</strong> - Proof of diver certification</li>\\n    <li><strong>Profile photos</strong> - Diver identification</li>\\n    <li><strong>Dive site photos</strong> - Site documentation and marketing</li>\\n    <li><strong>Signature documents</strong> - Captured signatures</li>\\n    <li><strong>Signed agreement PDFs</strong> - Completed waivers</li>\\n    <li><strong>Medical clearances</strong> - Physician letters</li>\\n    <li><strong>Eligibility proofs</strong> - ID documents for fee tiers</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Folder Management</h3>\\n<p>Views for folder organization:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>FolderCreateView, FolderUpdateView, FolderDeleteView</li>\\n    <li>FolderPermissionListView for access control</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Soft Delete</h3>\\n<p>Documents use soft delete with a trash feature:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>DocumentDeleteView moves to trash</li>\\n    <li>DocumentRestoreView recovers from trash</li>\\n    <li>DocumentPermanentDeleteView for final deletion</li>\\n    <li>EmptyTrashView clears all trashed documents</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.323543+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-12 13:38:34.009054+00	2026-01-12 13:38:34.040841+00	c67b253c-9b18-4541-af18-6f5ea6c519ab	\N	understanding-dcs	Understanding Decompression Sickness: Prevention and Recognition	published	public	[]	[]	Understanding Decompression Sickness: Prevention and Recognition	A comprehensive guide to decompression sickness (the bends), including risk factors, symptoms, prevention strategies, and what to do if you suspect DCS.			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/understanding-dcs/", "slug": "understanding-dcs", "title": "Understanding Decompression Sickness: Prevention and Recognition", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "Understanding Decompression Sickness: Prevention and Recognition", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "A comprehensive guide to decompression sickness (the bends), including risk factors, symptoms, prevention strategies, and what to do if you suspect DCS."}, "blocks": [{"id": "003bba03-b33a-4fc9-9cb8-745e7c255fd1", "data": {"content": "<p>Decompression sickness (DCS), commonly known as \\"the bends,\\" is one of the most serious risks divers face. Understanding what causes it, how to prevent it, and how to recognize symptoms is essential knowledge for every diver.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "5823a557-00c7-4314-9cb5-f45a060a21b8", "data": {"text": "What Causes DCS?", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "2f043aa3-55d5-4097-8e4a-1fd975373d04", "data": {"content": "<p>During a dive, nitrogen from the air we breathe dissolves into our body tissues under pressure. If we ascend too quickly, this nitrogen can form bubbles in our tissues and bloodstream, similar to how bubbles form when opening a carbonated drink. These bubbles can cause a range of symptoms from mild joint pain to life-threatening neurological damage.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "6e153e53-3758-4acc-90de-9ace3ff12cf8", "data": {"text": "Prevention Strategies", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "844525cc-e921-40a3-817e-21994ecea5ee", "data": {"content": "<ul><li>Always follow your dive computer or tables</li><li>Ascend slowly - no faster than 30 feet (9m) per minute</li><li>Perform safety stops at 15 feet (5m) for 3-5 minutes</li><li>Stay well hydrated before and after diving</li><li>Avoid flying within 18-24 hours after diving</li><li>Don't push no-decompression limits</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}, {"id": "ef566012-697b-46e8-822d-74ebf1f8c060", "data": {"text": "Recognizing Symptoms", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 5}, {"id": "2ddb9302-b7ff-4fee-9c23-26e0f448c13b", "data": {"content": "<p>Symptoms can appear immediately or up to 24 hours after diving:</p><ul><li>Joint pain (especially shoulders, elbows, knees)</li><li>Fatigue or unusual tiredness</li><li>Skin rash or itching</li><li>Dizziness or vertigo</li><li>Numbness or tingling</li><li>Difficulty breathing</li></ul><p><strong>If you suspect DCS, seek emergency medical care immediately and contact DAN (Divers Alert Network).</strong></p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 6}], "version": 1, "checksum": "2956a5cf44707576df35215b18d996d981719703550c1800bafb60f315d3b00e", "published_at": "2026-01-12T13:38:34.040532+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-12 13:38:34.040532+00	0	t	default	{}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	A comprehensive guide to decompression sickness (the bends), including risk factors, symptoms, prevention strategies, and what to do if you suspect DCS.	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1544551763-77ef2d0cfc6c?w=1200	post	9	["safety", "dcs", "decompression", "health", "emergency"]	110ef388-e1cb-4f55-b9bc-cdb7c59337d9
2026-01-09 15:42:29.735554+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.13196+00	2da48b70-358c-4ef4-94c8-97618b86a909	\N	help-divers-managing-certifications	Managing Certifications	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>The certification system tracks diver qualifications using a normalized model with agency-scoped certification levels.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Certification Levels</h3>\\n<p>Certifications are ranked for eligibility checking:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Scuba Diver</strong> - Entry level (rank 1)</li>\\n    <li><strong>Open Water Diver</strong> - Basic certification (rank 2)</li>\\n    <li><strong>Advanced Open Water</strong> - Intermediate (rank 3)</li>\\n    <li><strong>Rescue Diver</strong> - Advanced (rank 4)</li>\\n    <li><strong>Divemaster</strong> - Professional (rank 5)</li>\\n    <li><strong>Instructor</strong> - Teaching level (rank 6)</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Specialty Certifications</h3>\\n<p>Additional certifications tracked include:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Enriched Air (Nitrox) Diver</li>\\n    <li>Deep Diver</li>\\n    <li>Night Diver</li>\\n    <li>Wreck Diver</li>\\n    <li>Cavern Diver</li>\\n    <li>Underwater Photographer</li>\\n    <li>Peak Performance Buoyancy</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Verification Status</h3>\\n<p>Each certification tracks:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Verification status</strong> - Whether card has been verified</li>\\n    <li><strong>Verified by</strong> - Staff member who verified</li>\\n    <li><strong>Verified at</strong> - Date of verification</li>\\n    <li><strong>Document proof</strong> - Uploaded certification card photo</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Eligibility Checking</h3>\\n<p>When booking divers for excursions, the system automatically checks certification requirements. The <code>is_current</code> property validates expiration dates.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.13186+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.754337+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.149765+00	ec1dec5d-a7c6-48df-bffb-c392b23cc387	\N	help-divers-diver-categories	Diver Categories	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Diver categorization is used for agreement template targeting and eligibility.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Category Types</h3>\\n<p>The DiverCategory enumeration defines:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>all</strong> - Applies to all divers</li>\\n    <li><strong>certified</strong> - Certified divers only</li>\\n    <li><strong>student</strong> - Divers in training</li>\\n    <li><strong>dsd</strong> - Discover Scuba Diving participants</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Agreement Template Targeting</h3>\\n<p>Agreement templates can be configured for specific diver categories. When creating agreements, the system presents only templates appropriate for the diver's category.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Diver Type Classification</h3>\\n<p>Separate from category, divers are classified by their relationship with diving:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Activity</strong> - Does diving as an occasional activity</li>\\n    <li><strong>Identity</strong> - Diving is core to their identity</li>\\n</ul>\\n<p>This classification helps with marketing and communication targeting.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.149663+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.796629+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.204671+00	a206503a-40de-46ef-abfb-c7cf7851202f	\N	help-agreements-creating-agreements	Creating Agreements	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>SignableAgreement tracks the full workflow of liability waivers and other documents from creation through signature.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Creating a New Agreement</h3>\\n<ol>\\n    <li>Navigate to <strong>Agreements</strong></li>\\n    <li>Click <strong>New Agreement</strong></li>\\n    <li>Select an <strong>Agreement Template</strong> (radio buttons)</li>\\n    <li>Select the <strong>Diver</strong> from the dropdown</li>\\n    <li>Choose <strong>Delivery Method</strong>:\\n        <ul>\\n            <li><em>Link (copy signing URL)</em> - Generate shareable link</li>\\n            <li><em>Email (send to diver)</em> - Email the signing link</li>\\n            <li><em>In Person (sign on device)</em> - Sign at the shop</li>\\n        </ul>\\n    </li>\\n    <li>Set <strong>Expires In</strong> (7, 14, 30, 60, or 90 days)</li>\\n    <li>Click <strong>Create & Send</strong> or <strong>Save as Draft</strong></li>\\n</ol>\\n\\n<h3>Agreement Templates</h3>\\n<p>AgreementTemplate defines reusable document types:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>waiver</strong> - Liability release</li>\\n    <li><strong>medical</strong> - Medical disclosure</li>\\n    <li><strong>briefing</strong> - Dive briefing acknowledgment</li>\\n    <li><strong>code_of_conduct</strong> - Behavior agreement</li>\\n    <li><strong>rental</strong> - Equipment rental terms</li>\\n    <li><strong>training</strong> - Course enrollment</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Template Targeting</h3>\\n<p>Templates can target specific audiences:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>target_party_type</strong> - diver, employee, vendor, any</li>\\n    <li><strong>diver_category</strong> - all, certified, student, dsd</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.204557+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.811363+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.227645+00	d1d40dda-b000-4bf7-8d6c-de532960fab4	\N	help-agreements-tracking-status	Tracking Status	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Monitor agreement progress through the defined status workflow.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Agreement Status</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>draft</strong> - Created but not sent, content editable</li>\\n    <li><strong>sent</strong> - Delivered to signer, awaiting signature</li>\\n    <li><strong>signed</strong> - Completed with digital signature</li>\\n    <li><strong>void</strong> - Cancelled before signing</li>\\n    <li><strong>expired</strong> - Signing link expired without signature</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>List Filtering</h3>\\n<p>The agreements list provides filters to find specific documents:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Filter by status (dropdown)</li>\\n    <li>Search by diver name</li>\\n    <li>Date range filtering</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Agreement Detail View</h3>\\n<p>Each agreement shows:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Status badge with color coding</li>\\n    <li>Diver information</li>\\n    <li>Template used and version</li>\\n    <li>Timeline of status changes</li>\\n    <li>Digital signature details (if signed)</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Content Hash</h3>\\n<p>Agreements maintain a SHA-256 <code>content_hash</code> for integrity verification. Any content changes create revision records.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.227515+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.839333+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.274343+00	6de4aa06-1d59-4ae3-8dfc-12bdadc4121d	\N	help-medical-clearance-process	Clearance Process	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Physician clearance is required when questionnaire responses indicate potential health concerns.</p>\\n\\n<h3>When Clearance Required</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Questionnaire has flagged responses</li>\\n    <li>Diver reports significant medical conditions</li>\\n    <li>Previous clearance has expired</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Clearance Workflow</h3>\\n<ol>\\n    <li>System generates PDF with flagged conditions</li>\\n    <li>Diver takes form to physician</li>\\n    <li>Physician examines and signs clearance</li>\\n    <li>Diver returns signed form</li>\\n    <li>Staff uploads and records clearance</li>\\n</ol>\\n\\n<h3>Recording Clearance</h3>\\n<p>The DiverProfile stores:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><code>medical_clearance_date</code> - When obtained</li>\\n    <li><code>medical_clearance_valid_until</code> - Expiration</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Medical Provider Integration</h3>\\n<p>The MedicalProviderProfile and MedicalProviderRelationship models track relationships between divers and their healthcare providers.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.274211+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.852109+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.29547+00	2739e7d1-a6e1-443e-aaa2-ca0c4d6ae870	\N	help-protected-areas-managing-permits	Managing Permits	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>ProtectedArea models represent marine parks, reserves, and other regulated diving areas.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Protected Area Types</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>national_park</strong></li>\\n    <li><strong>marine_park</strong></li>\\n    <li><strong>reserve</strong></li>\\n    <li><strong>biosphere_reserve</strong></li>\\n    <li><strong>protected_area</strong></li>\\n    <li><strong>sanctuary</strong></li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Hierarchical Structure</h3>\\n<p>Protected areas support hierarchy through self-referential parent relationships. The <code>get_ancestors()</code> method returns the parent chain.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Unified Permit System</h3>\\n<p>ProtectedAreaPermit handles all permit types:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>guide</strong> - Guide credential (requires diver)</li>\\n    <li><strong>vessel</strong> - Boat permit (requires vessel_name, vessel_registration)</li>\\n    <li><strong>photography</strong> - Commercial photography permit</li>\\n    <li><strong>diving</strong> - Operator diving permit</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Permit Attributes</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><code>permit_number</code> - Unique per area+type</li>\\n    <li><code>issued_at</code>, <code>expires_at</code> - Validity period</li>\\n    <li><code>authorized_zones</code> - M2M (empty = all zones)</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.295357+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.873169+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.344789+00	cce47143-6a68-4fc7-8f25-879b8fb24eec	\N	help-system-ai-settings	AI Settings	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Configure AI-assisted features through the AI Settings page (<code>/staff/diveops/settings/ai/</code>).</p>\\n\\n<h3>AI Features</h3>\\n<p>The AISettings model configures:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Feature flags for AI capabilities</li>\\n    <li>Parameters for AI behavior</li>\\n    <li>Data access permissions</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Configuration Options</h3>\\n<p>Settings may include:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Enable/disable AI assistance</li>\\n    <li>Configure which data AI can access</li>\\n    <li>Set processing limits</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Privacy Considerations</h3>\\n<p>AI features are designed with privacy in mind:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Configurable data access</li>\\n    <li>Audit logging of AI operations</li>\\n    <li>Opt-out options available</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.344671+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-12 13:38:34.079015+00	2026-01-12 13:38:34.109432+00	30c09a72-0351-4ae4-b740-bab8fbf259ba	\N	night-dive-encounter-with-octopus	My Unforgettable Night Dive Encounter with a Giant Pacific Octopus	published	public	[]	[]	My Unforgettable Night Dive Encounter with a Giant Pacific Octopus	A personal account of an extraordinary night dive in the Pacific Northwest and an unexpected encounter with one of the ocean's most intelligent creatures.			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/night-dive-encounter-with-octopus/", "slug": "night-dive-encounter-with-octopus", "title": "My Unforgettable Night Dive Encounter with a Giant Pacific Octopus", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "My Unforgettable Night Dive Encounter with a Giant Pacific Octopus", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "A personal account of an extraordinary night dive in the Pacific Northwest and an unexpected encounter with one of the ocean's most intelligent creatures."}, "blocks": [{"id": "e135e072-78e8-4ca8-8b4a-9430818541c4", "data": {"content": "<p>It was a cold February evening when I slipped beneath the dark waters of Puget Sound. Night diving in the Pacific Northwest isn't for everyone - the water temperature hovered around 45F (7C), and visibility after sunset can be unpredictable. But something kept drawing me back to these waters, and on this particular night, I would discover why.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "86915a02-060d-49cc-9b92-b40ac04b1e0f", "data": {"text": "The Descent", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "c25e2c3a-f19e-4417-b52a-cd9c9bed70c5", "data": {"content": "<p>My dive buddy and I descended along the rocky wall, our primary lights cutting narrow paths through the darkness. The beam revealed sleeping rockfish tucked into crevices and tiny shrimp whose eyes reflected our lights like scattered stars. At about 40 feet, something unusual caught my attention - a subtle movement in the rocks that didn't match the gentle surge.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "b2651101-4f7b-4bf8-9789-e0b5df39637c", "data": {"text": "The Encounter", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "45fd194d-ddb0-479a-8d11-f4610c85a41e", "data": {"content": "<p>I swept my light across the area and there she was - a Giant Pacific Octopus, easily five feet from arm tip to arm tip, watching me with those remarkable, intelligent eyes. Instead of retreating into her den, she seemed curious, extending one arm toward my light while the others remained anchored to the rocks.</p><p>For nearly twenty minutes, we observed each other. She changed colors constantly - from deep red to mottled brown to almost white - and at one point reached out to touch my gloved hand with a single exploring arm. The suckers gripped briefly before releasing, as if testing whether I was friend or food (or perhaps just confused).</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}, {"id": "19d4106e-2988-420c-b10a-7cb75b88cd8c", "data": {"text": "A Lasting Impression", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 5}, {"id": "8c04ac3f-4a3a-4bd4-8e60-18830e0680ad", "data": {"content": "<p>That encounter changed how I think about diving and marine life. These creatures aren't just animals to photograph or check off a list - they're individuals with their own curiosity and intelligence. Every dive now feels like an opportunity for connection, a chance to be a guest in someone else's world.</p><p>If you ever get the chance to night dive in the Pacific Northwest, take it. You never know who you might meet in the darkness.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 6}], "version": 1, "checksum": "84ee997d1fb71ff0817bdf9fa215b3f18deb9e2f9a728d1bb4a9ce11bc434a74", "published_at": "2026-01-12T13:38:34.109116+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-12 13:38:34.109116+00	0	t	default	{}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	A personal account of an extraordinary night dive in the Pacific Northwest and an unexpected encounter with one of the ocean's most intelligent creatures.	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1545671913-b89ac1b4ac10?w=1200	post	5	["night diving", "octopus", "pacific northwest", "personal story", "adventure"]	99de6173-8156-47ad-b4fa-e64b01814a44
2026-01-09 15:42:29.690239+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.08501+00	4b6a40ec-8363-4dfb-af98-59224bccb152	\N	help-getting-started-dashboard-overview	Dashboard Overview	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>The Dive Operations Dashboard is your central hub for managing daily operations.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Dashboard Statistics</h3>\\n<p>The top of the dashboard displays key metrics:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Registered Divers</strong> - Total active diver profiles in the system</li>\\n    <li><strong>Active Excursions</strong> - Scheduled and in-progress dive trips</li>\\n    <li><strong>Pending Agreements</strong> - Waivers awaiting signature</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Weather Forecast</h3>\\n<p>The dashboard includes a weather widget showing current conditions and forecast for your dive shop location. Wind speed, direction, and conditions help with trip planning decisions.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Quick Navigation</h3>\\n<p>The sidebar provides access to all major sections:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Dive Operations</strong> - Excursions, Divers, Sites, Protected Areas, Agreements, Medical</li>\\n    <li><strong>Planning</strong> - Dive Plans and Dive Logs</li>\\n    <li><strong>System</strong> - Documents, Media, Audit Log</li>\\n    <li><strong>Configuration</strong> - Excursion Types, Agreement Templates, Catalog Items, AI Settings</li>\\n    <li><strong>Finance</strong> - Chart of Accounts, Payables</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.08479+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.726616+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.122967+00	ce7a9db3-02da-4867-a778-001d7aa76775	\N	help-divers-creating-profiles	Creating Diver Profiles	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Diver profiles (DiverProfile model) store comprehensive information about each diver including contact details, certifications, medical status, and equipment sizing.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Creating a New Diver</h3>\\n<ol>\\n    <li>Navigate to <strong>Divers</strong> in the sidebar</li>\\n    <li>Click <strong>Add Diver</strong></li>\\n    <li>Complete the form sections described below</li>\\n    <li>Click <strong>Create Diver</strong></li>\\n</ol>\\n\\n<h3>Personal Information (Required)</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>First Name</strong> - Diver's first name</li>\\n    <li><strong>Last Name</strong> - Diver's last name</li>\\n    <li><strong>Email</strong> - Primary contact email</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Certification Section</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Agency</strong> - Certification agency (PADI, SSI, NAUI, etc.)</li>\\n    <li><strong>Level</strong> - Certification level (Open Water, Advanced, Rescue, Divemaster, etc.)</li>\\n    <li><strong>Certification Number</strong> - Card number for verification</li>\\n    <li><strong>Certification Date</strong> - Date certification was issued</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Experience</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Total Dives</strong> - Logged dive count for experience tracking</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Medical Clearance</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Clearance Date</strong> - When physician clearance was obtained</li>\\n    <li><strong>Valid Until</strong> - Expiration date of medical clearance</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Diver Profile</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Diver Type</strong>:\\n        <ul>\\n            <li><em>Does Diving (Activity)</em> - Diving is an activity they do</li>\\n            <li><em>Diver (Identity)</em> - Diving is core to their identity</li>\\n        </ul>\\n    </li>\\n    <li><strong>Equipment Ownership</strong>:\\n        <ul>\\n            <li><em>None - Rents All</em> - Full rental customer</li>\\n            <li><em>Partial - Owns Some Gear</em> - Hybrid rental</li>\\n            <li><em>Full - Owns All Essential Gear</em> - Brings own equipment</li>\\n        </ul>\\n    </li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Body Measurements</h3>\\n<p>Used for equipment fitting and weighting calculations:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Weight (kg)</strong> - For buoyancy calculations</li>\\n    <li><strong>Height (cm)</strong> - For wetsuit sizing</li>\\n    <li><strong>Weight Required (kg)</strong> - Calculated neutral buoyancy weight</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Gear Sizes</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Wetsuit Size</strong> - e.g., M, L, XL</li>\\n    <li><strong>BCD Size</strong> - e.g., M, L, XL</li>\\n    <li><strong>Fin Size</strong> - e.g., M/L, 9-10</li>\\n    <li><strong>Mask Fit</strong> - e.g., Low volume, Standard</li>\\n    <li><strong>Glove Size</strong> - e.g., M, L, XL</li>\\n    <li><strong>Gear Notes</strong> - Additional preferences or requirements</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.122867+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.744966+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.140594+00	6fa98552-ab6d-4615-9eed-c438d73b11a9	\N	help-divers-emergency-contacts	Emergency Contacts	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>The EmergencyContact model stores emergency contact information with priority ordering for each diver.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Contact Information</h3>\\n<p>Each emergency contact includes:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Name</strong> - Contact's full name</li>\\n    <li><strong>Relationship</strong> - Relationship to diver</li>\\n    <li><strong>Phone numbers</strong> - Primary and alternate contact numbers</li>\\n    <li><strong>Priority</strong> - Order of contact (primary, secondary, etc.)</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Diver Relationships</h3>\\n<p>The DiverRelationship model tracks connections between divers:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Spouse</strong> - Married partner</li>\\n    <li><strong>Buddy</strong> - Preferred dive buddy</li>\\n    <li><strong>Friend</strong> - Social connection</li>\\n    <li><strong>Family</strong> - Family member</li>\\n    <li><strong>Instructor/Student</strong> - Training relationship</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Buddy Preferences</h3>\\n<p>Divers can mark preferred buddies. The system provides methods to query:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><code>spouse</code> - Find spouse relationship</li>\\n    <li><code>preferred_buddies</code> - List marked buddy preferences</li>\\n    <li><code>related_divers</code> - All connected divers</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.140496+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.769005+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.165679+00	4c55f7ac-d243-4732-aef5-0f33e040fb07	\N	help-bookings-managing-bookings	Managing Bookings	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>Bookings link divers to excursions and track reservation lifecycle.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Creating a Booking</h3>\\n<ol>\\n    <li>Open the excursion detail page</li>\\n    <li>Click <strong>Add Booking</strong></li>\\n    <li>Search for and select a diver</li>\\n    <li>System performs eligibility checks automatically</li>\\n    <li>Confirm the booking</li>\\n</ol>\\n\\n<h3>Booking Status</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>pending</strong> - Reservation made, not confirmed</li>\\n    <li><strong>confirmed</strong> - Booking confirmed</li>\\n    <li><strong>checked_in</strong> - Diver arrived and checked in</li>\\n    <li><strong>cancelled</strong> - Booking cancelled</li>\\n    <li><strong>no_show</strong> - Diver didn't arrive</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Eligibility Checking</h3>\\n<p>Before booking confirmation, the system validates:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Diver has required certification level for excursion type</li>\\n    <li>Medical clearance is current (if required)</li>\\n    <li>Waiver is signed and valid</li>\\n    <li>No scheduling conflicts</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Eligibility Overrides</h3>\\n<p>The EligibilityOverride model allows bypassing requirements:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>One override per booking only</li>\\n    <li>Requires <strong>approved_by</strong> staff member</li>\\n    <li>Requires documented <strong>reason</strong></li>\\n    <li>Tracks which requirement was bypassed</li>\\n    <li>Creates immutable audit trail</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Price Snapshot</h3>\\n<p>The booking captures <code>price_snapshot</code> at creation time. This ensures price immutability even if the excursion price changes later.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.165556+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-12 06:35:52.393096+00	2026-01-12 06:35:52.417935+00	dc5443cd-a453-4567-9ff1-44b671dbbe05	\N	contact	Contact Happy Diving	published	public	[]	[]					index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/contact/", "slug": "contact", "title": "Contact Happy Diving", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": ""}, "blocks": [{"id": "65ab38e7-7803-4403-9598-17f21d87f153", "data": {"text": "Get in Touch", "level": 1}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "99b3ade4-544f-4997-921f-04802185cb28", "data": {"content": "<p>Ready to plan your diving adventure? We'd love to hear from you!</p>\\n<p><strong>Location:</strong> Playa del Carmen, Quintana Roo, Mexico</p>\\n<p><strong>Phone:</strong> <a href=\\"tel:+529841234567\\">+52 984 123 4567</a></p>\\n<p><strong>WhatsApp:</strong> <a href=\\"https://wa.me/529841234567\\">+52 984 123 4567</a></p>\\n<p><strong>Email:</strong> <a href=\\"mailto:info@happydiving.mx\\">info@happydiving.mx</a></p>\\n<p><strong>Hours:</strong> Daily 7:00 AM - 6:00 PM</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "30367571-9199-478a-8d8e-64dd3033ff74", "data": {}, "type": "divider", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "7494a3b5-73c3-4140-b046-2898e6e748d4", "data": {"text": "How to Find Us", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "623c1053-8f46-4a3a-916d-ecdf0aa221b3", "data": {"content": "<p>We're located in the heart of Playa del Carmen, just a short walk from the beach and 5th Avenue. Hotel pickup is available for all diving excursions.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}, {"id": "1dd1f1e1-0da0-4ad8-83bf-5f68bd94f484", "data": {"url": "mailto:info@happydiving.mx", "text": "Send Us a Message"}, "type": "cta", "sequence": 5}], "version": 1, "checksum": "b7b4ec40251bf6058f476e9f8f4116108f30c993b0f89e580c23dd8a280ee37d", "published_at": "2026-01-12T06:35:52.417667+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-12 06:35:52.417667+00	0	t	default	{}	1	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.782687+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.184132+00	9f47b677-b359-4bb5-9b0c-f6db296f4f26	\N	help-bookings-recurring-series	Recurring Series	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>ExcursionSeries enables scheduling recurring excursions using RFC 5545 recurrence rules.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Creating a Recurring Series</h3>\\n<ol>\\n    <li>Open an existing excursion</li>\\n    <li>Click <strong>Make Recurring</strong></li>\\n    <li>Configure the recurrence pattern</li>\\n    <li>Set series defaults (capacity, price, meeting place)</li>\\n    <li>Save the series</li>\\n</ol>\\n\\n<h3>Recurrence Rules</h3>\\n<p>The RecurrenceRule model stores RFC 5545 RRULE strings:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>FREQ=WEEKLY;BYDAY=SA</strong> - Every Saturday</li>\\n    <li><strong>FREQ=DAILY</strong> - Every day</li>\\n    <li><strong>FREQ=WEEKLY;BYDAY=MO,WE,FR</strong> - Monday, Wednesday, Friday</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Series Attributes</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>excursion_type</strong> - Template for generated excursions</li>\\n    <li><strong>dive_site</strong> - Default site</li>\\n    <li><strong>capacity_default</strong> - Default max divers</li>\\n    <li><strong>price_default</strong> - Default price</li>\\n    <li><strong>meeting_place</strong> - Where divers meet</li>\\n    <li><strong>window_days</strong> - How far ahead to generate occurrences</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Series Status</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>draft</strong> - Not yet active</li>\\n    <li><strong>active</strong> - Generating occurrences</li>\\n    <li><strong>paused</strong> - Temporarily stopped</li>\\n    <li><strong>retired</strong> - Permanently ended</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Exceptions</h3>\\n<p>RecurrenceException handles individual date modifications:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>cancelled</strong> - Skip this occurrence</li>\\n    <li><strong>rescheduled</strong> - Move to different time</li>\\n    <li><strong>added</strong> - Extra occurrence</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.184015+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.860805+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.314377+00	1092d33c-b7f0-4fc4-874e-db692be2c942	\N	help-protected-areas-zone-rules	Zone Rules	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>ProtectedAreaZone divides protected areas into zones with specific regulations.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Zone Types</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>core</strong> - No-take zone, highest protection</li>\\n    <li><strong>buffer</strong> - Buffer zone around core</li>\\n    <li><strong>use</strong> - Recreational use zone</li>\\n    <li><strong>restoration</strong> - Restoration area</li>\\n    <li><strong>research</strong> - Research-only access</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Zone Permissions</h3>\\n<p>Each zone defines:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><code>diving_allowed</code></li>\\n    <li><code>anchoring_allowed</code></li>\\n    <li><code>fishing_allowed</code></li>\\n    <li><code>requires_guide</code></li>\\n    <li><code>requires_permit</code></li>\\n    <li><code>max_divers</code> - Capacity limit</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Zone Rules</h3>\\n<p>ProtectedAreaRule enforces specific regulations:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><strong>Rule types</strong>: max_depth, max_divers, certification, equipment, time, activity, conduct</li>\\n    <li><strong>Applies to</strong>: diver, group, vessel, operator</li>\\n    <li><strong>Enforcement levels</strong>: info, warn, block</li>\\n    <li><strong>Effective dating</strong>: effective_start, effective_end</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Compliance Checking</h3>\\n<p>Rules use comparison operators (lte, gte, eq, in, contains, required_true) against values. The system can block bookings that violate blocking-level rules.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.31424+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-09 15:42:29.86901+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.334258+00	211b629f-f71f-4fbc-be91-561bbbd7be7b	\N	help-system-audit-log	Audit Log	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>The audit log (<code>/staff/diveops/audit-log/</code>) tracks all system activity for accountability and troubleshooting.</p>\\n\\n<h3>What's Logged</h3>\\n<p>The django-audit-log package records:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Record creation, updates, and deletions</li>\\n    <li>Status changes (booking confirmed, agreement signed, etc.)</li>\\n    <li>User actions with timestamps</li>\\n    <li>IP addresses and user agents</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Viewing the Log</h3>\\n<p>The AuditLogView displays entries with filtering:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Date range</li>\\n    <li>User who performed action</li>\\n    <li>Action type</li>\\n    <li>Record type (model)</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Entry Details</h3>\\n<p>Each audit entry includes:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Timestamp</li>\\n    <li>Actor (user who performed action)</li>\\n    <li>Action description</li>\\n    <li>Affected record</li>\\n    <li>Before/after values for changes</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Use Cases</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Investigate who made a change</li>\\n    <li>Track workflow progression</li>\\n    <li>Verify compliance actions</li>\\n    <li>Debug issues</li>\\n    <li>Security monitoring</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.334099+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-12 13:38:34.048847+00	2026-01-12 13:38:34.070905+00	b3edae55-9028-4f31-9353-5157b41f978c	\N	coral-reef-conservation	Coral Reef Conservation: How Divers Can Make a Difference	published	public	[]	[]	Coral Reef Conservation: How Divers Can Make a Difference	Discover the threats facing coral reefs worldwide and learn practical ways you can help protect these vital ecosystems as a diver.			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/coral-reef-conservation/", "slug": "coral-reef-conservation", "title": "Coral Reef Conservation: How Divers Can Make a Difference", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "Coral Reef Conservation: How Divers Can Make a Difference", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "Discover the threats facing coral reefs worldwide and learn practical ways you can help protect these vital ecosystems as a diver."}, "blocks": [{"id": "d489a977-0042-4346-acc5-28eb3045cb28", "data": {"content": "<p>Coral reefs cover less than 1% of the ocean floor but support approximately 25% of all marine species. As divers, we have a unique connection to these underwater ecosystems and a responsibility to help protect them for future generations.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "16d3f123-e520-4194-adf4-d108a07e19c9", "data": {"text": "Threats to Coral Reefs", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "67475e04-7cbb-40ef-966b-750e74f09024", "data": {"content": "<p>Coral reefs face numerous threats, both local and global:</p><ul><li><strong>Climate Change</strong> - Rising ocean temperatures cause coral bleaching</li><li><strong>Ocean Acidification</strong> - Absorbed CO2 makes it harder for corals to build skeletons</li><li><strong>Pollution</strong> - Runoff from agriculture and urban areas</li><li><strong>Overfishing</strong> - Disrupts reef ecosystem balance</li><li><strong>Physical Damage</strong> - Anchor damage, careless divers, and destructive fishing practices</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "22391b32-0769-4c80-9bff-d94b79545248", "data": {"text": "How Divers Can Help", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "5eabc193-b510-44cb-a6d1-61eb03c0ba19", "data": {"content": "<ul><li><strong>Perfect Your Buoyancy</strong> - Good buoyancy control prevents accidental reef contact</li><li><strong>Choose Reef-Safe Sunscreen</strong> - Avoid oxybenzone and octinoxate</li><li><strong>Participate in Reef Cleanups</strong> - Remove debris and fishing line</li><li><strong>Report Marine Life Sightings</strong> - Citizen science helps researchers track reef health</li><li><strong>Support Conservation Organizations</strong> - Donate to or volunteer with reef protection groups</li><li><strong>Spread Awareness</strong> - Share your underwater experiences and educate others</li></ul>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}], "version": 1, "checksum": "239a5ab86f2ecc6b09498810f150e2727d8be4402729461cdede4ce114af019e", "published_at": "2026-01-12T13:38:34.070606+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-12 13:38:34.070606+00	0	t	default	{}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	Discover the threats facing coral reefs worldwide and learn practical ways you can help protect these vital ecosystems as a diver.	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1546026423-cc4642628d2b?w=1200	post	8	["conservation", "coral reef", "environment", "sustainability", "ocean health"]	8a93ab27-2fd5-4037-bfdc-70f27c44f73b
2026-01-09 16:06:21.06781+00	2026-01-09 16:38:29.353053+00	d791dfc4-1aa1-4545-be26-01317c1ae411	\N	help-system-automated-documentation	Automated Documentation	published	role	["staff"]	[]					index, follow	{"blocks": [{"data": {"content": "<p>DiveOps includes tools for automated documentation with screenshots.</p>\\n\\n<h3>Screenshot Capture</h3>\\n<p>The <code>scripts/capture_help_screenshots.py</code> script uses Playwright to:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Navigate to application pages</li>\\n    <li>Capture full-page screenshots</li>\\n    <li>Capture cropped component screenshots</li>\\n    <li>Organize by page type (lists, details, forms, system)</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Interface Crawler</h3>\\n<p>The <code>scripts/crawl_interface.py</code> extracts UI elements:</p>\\n<ul>\\n    <li>Form fields with labels and types</li>\\n    <li>Buttons and actions</li>\\n    <li>Table structures</li>\\n    <li>Navigation links</li>\\n</ul>\\n\\n<h3>Running the Tools</h3>\\n<pre>\\n# Capture screenshots\\npython scripts/capture_help_screenshots.py --headed\\n\\n# Crawl interface\\npython scripts/crawl_interface.py\\n\\n# Embed screenshots in CMS\\npython manage.py embed_help_screenshots\\n</pre>\\n\\n<h3>Output Locations</h3>\\n<ul>\\n    <li><code>media/help/screenshots/</code> - Screenshot images</li>\\n    <li><code>docs/interface_analysis/</code> - Interface analysis JSON</li>\\n</ul>"}, "type": "rich_text"}]}	2026-01-09 16:38:29.352946+00	0	t	help-article	{}	\N	\N			page	\N	[]	\N
2026-01-11 11:05:38.933355+00	2026-01-11 11:05:38.957804+00	5555f629-cd77-4519-a09a-fc32c1739d1e	2026-01-12 13:38:33.856917+00	top-10-dive-sites-cozumel	Top 10 Dive Sites in Cozumel You Can't Miss	published	public	[]	[]	Top 10 Dive Sites in Cozumel You Can't Miss	Discover the best underwater adventures Cozumel has to offer, from dramatic wall dives to colorful reef gardens teeming with marine life.			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/top-10-dive-sites-cozumel/", "slug": "top-10-dive-sites-cozumel", "title": "Top 10 Dive Sites in Cozumel You Can't Miss", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "Top 10 Dive Sites in Cozumel You Can't Miss", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "Discover the best underwater adventures Cozumel has to offer, from dramatic wall dives to colorful reef gardens teeming with marine life."}, "blocks": [{"id": "f2be3915-2bc2-445e-b76e-920d7c13ed33", "data": {"content": "<p>Cozumel, Mexico, is consistently ranked among the world's top dive destinations, and for good reason. With crystal-clear waters, dramatic wall dives, and an incredible variety of marine life, this Caribbean island offers something for divers of every skill level.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}, {"id": "7a079ef3-e646-4c66-8c7a-8dad8267e857", "data": {"text": "1. Palancar Reef", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 1}, {"id": "075e47b4-7a21-421c-9a5f-a6e9e97892f8", "data": {"content": "<p>Perhaps the most famous dive site in Cozumel, Palancar Reef is actually a series of dive sites along a massive reef system. The towering coral formations, swim-throughs, and abundant marine life make this a must-dive destination. Look for eagle rays, sea turtles, and the occasional nurse shark.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 2}, {"id": "edf86960-8534-4ab5-8371-281ed5a5384e", "data": {"text": "2. Santa Rosa Wall", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 3}, {"id": "192656cb-f381-445f-88ee-3e740c412df0", "data": {"content": "<p>For experienced divers, Santa Rosa Wall offers one of the most exhilarating drift dives in the Caribbean. The wall drops from 50 feet to well beyond recreational limits, featuring massive sponges, black coral, and deep overhangs perfect for exploring.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 4}, {"id": "3df4c167-282d-4322-ace2-1d8f6f6e0cb5", "data": {"text": "3. Columbia Deep", "level": 2}, "type": "heading", "sequence": 5}, {"id": "8322bdf3-243e-4d1d-b0c0-4cb1490fe57e", "data": {"content": "<p>Home to some of the largest coral pinnacles in Cozumel, Columbia Deep is where you'll find stunning formations rising from 80-100 feet. The area is known for encounters with spotted eagle rays and large groupers.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 6}, {"id": "736179d2-9a42-4be2-93bf-47286ea37a76", "data": {"text": "Book your Cozumel diving adventure with us today!", "title": "Ready to Dive Cozumel?", "button_url": "/excursions/", "button_text": "View Excursions"}, "type": "call_to_action", "sequence": 7}], "version": 1, "checksum": "5cdfcfd8d3b092923e0fb887d592fa5c10d96ff2e227fddd38d1bdd59cbf1f41", "published_at": "2026-01-11T11:05:38.957599+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-11 11:05:38.957599+00	0	t	default	{}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	Discover the best underwater adventures Cozumel has to offer, from dramatic wall dives to colorful reef gardens teeming with marine life.	https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1544551763-46a013bb70d5?w=1200	post	8	["cozumel", "mexico", "caribbean", "wall diving", "reef"]	ecf98da2-4669-4486-a712-0ac9a942fc93
