2026-01-12 15:31:00.310259+00	2026-01-12 15:37:22.681087+00	eb9c410f-1941-46d2-83da-2f1b75af1e50	\N	2024-08-07-i-just-read-a-post-in	I just read a post in a diving group from an open water student exp...	published	public	[]	[]	I just read a post in a diving group from an open water student exp...	I just read a post in a diving group from an open water student expressing frustration with their instructor failing to teach them how to succeed in...			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/2024-08-07-i-just-read-a-post-in/", "slug": "2024-08-07-i-just-read-a-post-in", "title": "I just read a post in a diving group from an open water student exp...", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "I just read a post in a diving group from an open water student exp...", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "I just read a post in a diving group from an open water student expressing frustration with their instructor failing to teach them how to succeed in..."}, "blocks": [{"id": "cc394a53-ff4c-4f98-be17-5acaa8f52df9", "data": {"content": "<p>I just read a post in a diving group from an open water student expressing frustration with their instructor failing to teach them how to succeed in the straightline reciprocal compass navigation requirement.  I was especially disheartened to hear they didn't get the necessary instruction and failed the course and they were not allowed to continue to open water dives 3 & 4.</p><p>First this is a dive optional skill that can be taught and retaught and repeated again and again so it blows my mind any instructor would summarily decide on dive 2 that they would issue the student the intermediate scuba diver certification rather than teach the struggling student and allow them more opportunities to demonstrate it on the next dives in sequence.</p><p>I made a video for this student and others who I hope will benefit from my method of teaching something that takes about three minutes to teach and when paired with some dry land practice guarantees success for meeting the performance requirement.   It really pisses me off when I hear stories like this. It's not only traumatic for the failing student who walks away from the experience with a bad taste in their mouth about dive education it reflects poorly on our profession when instructors dont take the time to teach people who struggle and then fail them.</p><p>This is how I teach the skill.</p>"}, "type": "rich_text", "sequence": 0}], "version": 1, "checksum": "d6b01579fbbc2bc6b32443b4d1b3e7435016aa061e6ee07bfc7845744a96d803", "published_at": "2026-01-12T15:31:00.317939+00:00", "access_control": {"level": "public", "required_roles": [], "required_entitlements": []}, "published_by_id": "1"}	2026-01-12 15:31:00.317939+00	0	t	default	{"source": "facebook", "original_date": "2024-08-07"}	1	70c922aa-9fcb-4b5e-8736-e82206cf5c37	I just read a post in a diving group from an open water student expressing frustration with their instructor failing to teach them how to succeed in the straightline reciprocal compass navigation...	https://scontent.fcun1-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/485154764_1036055171874679_3601010924540205523_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_p180x540_tt6&_nc_cat=102&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=833d8c&_nc_ohc=yLMuP6IoeOAQ7kNvwEDl-Uu&_nc_oc=AdnEUafD1SWrxZEsrDidWUzuiI3mC259ppOGVI09xBGBGRbD0103yy7jY8gxu8Y2xY0&_nc_zt=23&_nc_ht=scontent.fcun1-1.fna&_nc_gid=d6CcI9QPxoTD4XXoV2KbeA&oh=00_Afo2ox3oDZt_WL4VQ2LJ1xA7tNrZSTIGxVSoLja-Y44o5A&oe=696AF509	post	1	["facebook-import", "buceo-feliz"]	1ebb6e5c-53b0-41b9-b643-fb7823358e35
2026-01-12 15:31:00.259149+00	2026-01-12 15:37:22.688482+00	6bcfe9ff-a14d-4b83-97a6-5741d60b0bd2	\N	2024-10-02-food-for-thought-one-of-the	Food for thought.  	published	public	[]	[]	Food for thought.  	Food for thought.  One of the more awkward yet crucial safety skills students stumble with is the low pressure inflator hose disconnect drill. The last...			index, follow	{"meta": {"path": "/2024-10-02-food-for-thought-one-of-the/", "slug": "2024-10-02-food-for-thought-one-of-the", "title": "Food for thought.  ", "robots": "index, follow", "seo_title": "Food for thought.  ", "og_image_url": "", "seo_description": "Food for thought.  One of the more awkward yet crucial safety skills students stumble with is the low pressure inflator hose disconnect drill. The last..."}, "blocks": [{"id": "74033bce-ab38-4a0b-b016-a4885792f58f", "data": {"content": "<p>Food for thought.</p><p>One of the more awkward yet crucial safety skills students stumble with is the low pressure inflator hose disconnect drill.</p><p>The last time I taught for another dive shop the rental gear was so corroded the student couldn't possibly learn the skill.  I myself had a hard time disconnecting the inflator hose.</p><p>This was frustrating for them, and for me.  It's such an important potentially life saving skill. A failed runaway inflater is one of the most common problems that can cause an uncontrolled rapid ascent.</p><p>So something I always do before I teach is to make sure the inflator hose my student has is easy and smooth to operate correctly.</p><p>Regular cleaning with vinegar or a dip in the ultrasonic plus a small dab of silicone applied with the tip of a probe keeps things moving as they should.</p><p>You may wonder why I'm more expensive to study with than the cattle boat operators.  This is one of the reasons.   I make the skills easier to learn because I put more time into the details.  Here's all it takes not to cut corners.  But that costs more because it takes more time in and out 